                "authorUrl": "https://faithwilding.com/",
                "abstract": "This article delves into an in-depth discussion with Faith Wilding, selft described Eco-feminist Artist and Activist. The discussion explores the complexities and dynamics of the 'Artworld' through various phases of Faith's extensive career. Spanning from traditional media to performance art and from feminist activism to electronic culture, the artist reflects on her varied experiences across different facets of the art scene. She highlights the fragmented nature of the art economy and stresses the importance of adaptability and tactical innovation for oppositional cultural producers. The artist also critiques the conventional art institutional system that emphasizes spectacles and hierarchical structures, advocating instead for a more flexible and collaborative approach that empowers the so-called \"bottom feeders\" of the art world. Furthermore, she discusses the shifting trends within the art world, including the recent embrace of electronic and network art by mainstream institutions, and reflects on her current involvement with the collective practice of SubRosa, a cyberfeminist organization she co-led with fellow artist Hyla Willis, which focuses on interdisciplinary and activist work in electronic culture. In their presentation of the BioTech Sex and Gender Education Show, SubRosa facilitated a genetically sound and professionally approved union between the author's genetic materials and those of Joel Slayton (founder of the CADRE lab at SJSU, archived herehttp://cyberfeminism.net/sex-and-gender-ed-show/). ",
